# Test Suite Command-Line Flags

## Overview

DemiEngine now supports granular test execution with specific flags to run different test suites independently. This makes it easier to focus on specific types of tests during development.

## Available Test Flags

### Run All Tests
```bash
./bin/demi-engine --test
# or
./bin/demi-engine -t
```

Runs all test suites in order:
1. Unit tests (C++ test framework)
2. In-assembly tests (validation)
3. Integration tests (.hex files)

**Use when:** You want comprehensive testing before committing changes.

---

### Run Unit Tests Only
```bash
./bin/demi-engine --unit-test
# or
./bin/demi-engine -ut
```

Runs only the C++ unit tests (79 tests).

**Features tested:**
- Assembler functionality
- Parser operations
- CPU instruction validation
- Memory bounds checking
- Error handling
- Negative test cases

**Use when:** 
- Testing core assembler/parser changes
- Quick feedback on code changes
- CI/CD pipelines (fastest test suite)

**Average runtime:** ~1-2 seconds

---

### Run Integration Tests Only
```bash
./bin/demi-engine --integration-test
# or
./bin/demi-engine -it
```

Runs only the integration tests (42 .hex file tests).

**Features tested:**
- End-to-end program execution
- CPU instruction implementation
- Device I/O
- Complex program flows
- Real-world scenarios

**Use when:**
- Testing CPU instruction changes
- Verifying device implementations
- Testing complete programs
- Regression testing

**Average runtime:** ~2-3 seconds

---

### Run In-Assembly Tests Only
```bash
./bin/demi-engine --assembly-test
# or
./bin/demi-engine -at
```

Runs only the in-assembly test validation (61 tests across 10 files).

**Features tested:**
- Test syntax parsing
- Test structure validation
- Assertion parsing
- Complex test scenarios

**Use when:**
- Testing #test/#assert directive parsing
- Validating test file structure
- Quick feedback on assembly test files
- Developing new test cases

**Average runtime:** ~1 second

---

## Usage Examples

### Quick Unit Test During Development
```bash
# Make a change to assembler
vim src/assembler/assembler.cpp

# Quick validation
./bin/demi-engine -ut
```

### Test Integration After CPU Changes
```bash
# Modify CPU instruction
vim src/engine/opcodes/opcodes_consolidated.cpp

# Test with integration suite
./bin/demi-engine -it
```

### Validate New Assembly Test Files
```bash
# Create new test
vim tests/asm/my_new_test.asm

# Validate structure
./bin/demi-engine -at
```

### Full Testing Before Commit
```bash
# Run everything
./bin/demi-engine -t
```

## Test Suite Comparison

| Flag | Tests | Runtime | Best For |
|------|-------|---------|----------|
| `-t` / `--test` | All (182) | ~5-7s | Pre-commit, releases |
| `-ut` / `--unit-test` | 79 | ~1-2s | Rapid iteration, CI |
| `-it` / `--integration-test` | 42 | ~2-3s | CPU/device changes |
| `-at` / `--assembly-test` | 61 | ~1s | Test file validation |

## Exit Codes

All test flags exit with:
- `0` - All tests passed
- `1` - One or more tests failed (for unit/integration tests)
- `0` - Validation complete (for assembly tests, which only validate structure)

## CI/CD Integration

### GitHub Actions Example
```yaml
- name: Run Unit Tests
  run: ./bin/demi-engine --unit-test

- name: Run Integration Tests
  run: ./bin/demi-engine --integration-test

- name: Run Assembly Test Validation
  run: ./bin/demi-engine --assembly-test
```

### Makefile Integration
```makefile
test: build
	./bin/demi-engine --test

test-unit: build
	./bin/demi-engine --unit-test

test-integration: build
	./bin/demi-engine --integration-test

test-assembly: build
	./bin/demi-engine --assembly-test

.PHONY: test test-unit test-integration test-assembly
```

## Tips

1. **Fastest Feedback Loop**: Use `-ut` during active development
2. **CPU Changes**: Always run `-it` after modifying CPU instructions
3. **Assembly Files**: Use `-at` to quickly validate test syntax
4. **Before Push**: Run full `-t` to ensure everything passes

## Future Enhancements

- `--test-filter <pattern>` - Run specific test names matching pattern
- `--test-category <name>` - Run tests from specific category
- `--test-parallel` - Parallel test execution
- `--test-verbose` - Detailed test output
- Assembly test execution (currently only validates structure)

